Consider the following
• The north part of Dublin City has more people than any of the other parts of the Greater Dublin Area and has had over the last 25 years – yet has only a partial LUJAS line;
• National Transport Authority (NTA) study shows that the largest increase in in morning peak travel (0700-1000)is inside the M50 – not to/from the Airport which hasx peak time of 0600 during hte working week;
• the need for quick access between the Airport and the City centre is a red-herring given as another NTA study found that
1. Almost half (46%) had a journey time of less than 30 minutes to the Airport;
2. Three-quarters (75%) had a journey time of less than one hour to the Airport;
3. Three quarters(75%) of all trips were either for holiday/leisure (nearly 50%) or visiting friends/relatives (over 25%), which does not suggest people being time-constrained;
4. Less than one-third of Airport trips originated in Dublin City Centre/south part of Dublin City;
5. Less than one-seventh (14%) of Airport trips were business related.
Those who feel time-constrained in travelling between Dublin City Centre and the Airport have the options of taking taxis which can use the Port Tunnel or bus lanes.

